    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>I had similar problem with <strong>IntelliJ</strong> when tried to run some Groovy scripts.\nHere is how I solved it.</p>\n\n<p>Go to \"Project Structure\"-> \"Project\" -> \"Project language level\" and select \"SDK default\". This should use the same SDK for all project modules.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 263656,
      "reputation" : 79563,
      "user_id" : 549372,
      "user_type" : "registered",
      "accept_rate" : 100,
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/430cfd8b3056a0425f950cb1c6abd208?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
      "display_name" : "Martin Zeitler",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/549372/martin-zeitler"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 50,
    "last_activity_date" : 1603519486,
    "last_edit_date" : 1603519486,
    "creation_date" : 1603518939,
    "answer_id" : 64510447,
    "question_id" : 58125830,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<p>This is a setting in IntelliJ IDEA (<code>$JAVA_HOME</code> and language level were set to 1.8):</p>\n<p><code>File</code> &gt; <code>Settings</code> &gt; <code>Build, Execution, Deployment</code> &gt; <code>Gradle</code> &gt; <code>Gradle JVM</code></p>\n<p>Select eg. <code>Project SDK (corretto-1.8)</code> (or any other compatible version).</p>\n<p>Then delete the <code>build</code> directory and restart the IDE.</p>\n"
  }, {
